    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid buildup, also known as lactic acidosis, is a common phenomenon that occurs during high-intensity interval training (HIIT) and other anaerobic exercises. It's a result of the body's anaerobic energy system kicking in, where your muscles switch from relying on oxygen to relying on stored energy sources like glycogen and ATP. This process is initiated by the enzyme pyruvate kinase, which converts phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) into pyruvate, producing a small amount of ATP and lactic acid as a byproduct. The lactic acid is then transported into the muscle cells, where it's converted back into glucose and used for energy.\n\nHowever, the body doesn't have a dedicated mechanism for clearing out lactic acid immediately after exercise. Instead, it's stored in the muscles and liver, where it's eventually converted back into glucose and released into the bloodstream. This process is facilitated by the enzyme lactate dehydrogenase, which converts lactic acid into pyruvate. The pyruvate is then fed into the citric acid cycle, where it's converted into ATP, NADH, and other energy-rich molecules.\n\nIt's worth noting that",
      "source": "target",
